  "timeframe": "1D",
  "market_context": "Daily chart of gold (XAUUSD) showing a series of swing highs and lows including stacked equal lows on the sell side and successive highs on the buy side, providing a real example to classify which swings are relevant versus failure swings.",
  "key_observation": "Stacked/equal lows close to each other are failure swings that cannot be trusted for reversals; only the swing with valid separation qualifies as the relevant swing that price must sweep before a reaction can be anticipated.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Mark out previous highs and lows on the XAUUSD daily chart, starting with the lows.",
    "Step 2: Identify the cluster of stacked/equal lows on the sell side and ask whether price could be trusted to reverse from any of them.",
    "Step 3: Conclude that none of the stacked lows are tradable because the deepest one is the relevant low that must be taken out first.",
    "Step 4: Move to the upside, identify a high with good separation from prior highs and label it as a relevant swing high.",
    "Step 5: Observe that when price fails to reverse from that high and pushes higher, the new higher high becomes the relevant high while the prior level remains relevant — yielding two relevant swings to monitor.",
    "Step 6: Note that on the trade into the relevant swing, a candle 2 closure forms, providing the location to apply the fractal model.",
    "Step 7: Define the trade targets as the opposite side of the range or the failure swings on the way there.",
    "Step 8: Repeat the process forward in time — after price trades into the relevant low and reacts lower, the new pullback high with good separation becomes the next relevant high; gaps too close to prior highs are dismissed as failure swings."
  ],
  "outcome": null,
  "lessons": "Only swings with valid separation are relevant and tradable for reversals; stacked or closely-spaced highs and lows are failure swings that act as liquidity targets, not reaction levels. Always wait for the relevant swing to be swept before applying the fractal model.",
